class Solution {
    public int lengthOfLongestSubstring(String s) {
        Set<Character> seen = new HashSet<>();
        int maxLength = 0;
        int start = 0;
        for (int end = 0; end < s.length(); end++) {
            while (seen.contains(s.charAt(end))) {
                seen.remove(s.charAt(start));
                start++;
            }
            seen.add(s.charAt(end));
            maxLength = Math.max(maxLength, end - start + 1);
        }
        return maxLength;
    }
}
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n)
space complexity: O(min(n, charset size))
explanation: Uses a sliding window approach with a HashSet to track seen characters. The window expands until a duplicate is encountered, then the window slides forward.  The maximum length is tracked and returned.  The space complexity is limited by the HashSet, which can store at most the size of the input string's unique characters.

